goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand the typical impact of a disaster in terms of human life.

import seaborn as sns
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='ignore')
    yearly_disasters = data.groupby('Year').size().reset_index(name='Number of Disasters')
    sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Number of Disasters', data=yearly_disasters)
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of disasters over time?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
```

import seaborn as sns
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    disaster_counts = data['Entity'].value_counts()
    sns.barplot(x=disaster_counts.index, y=disaster_counts.values)
    plt.xlabel('Disaster Type')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('What is the most common type of disaster?')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
```

import seaborn as sns
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='ignore')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    ax = sns.boxplot(x='Entity', y='Deaths', data=data)
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha='right')
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the average number of deaths per disaster?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
